1
00:00:05,560 --> 00:00:06,800
Cool.

2
00:00:06,800 --> 00:00:13,000
Hello, everyone, and welcome
to lecture 3 of CME 295.

3
00:00:13,000 --> 00:00:15,360
So today is a very
exciting day, because we're

4
00:00:15,360 --> 00:00:19,920
going to finally introduce
large language models.

5
00:00:19,920 --> 00:00:22,000
But I guess before we
go into that I'm just

6
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:26,360
going to start, traditionally,
with some announcements.

7
00:00:26,360 --> 00:00:30,220
So some of you wanted to have
the slides before the class.

8
00:00:30,220 --> 00:00:32,360
So just a heads up
that in case you

9
00:00:32,360 --> 00:00:36,240
want to use the slides
to do some annotations,

10
00:00:36,240 --> 00:00:37,660
they're on the
website right now.

11
00:00:37,660 --> 00:00:39,800
So feel free to get them.

12
00:00:39,800 --> 00:00:43,200
And with Shervin, we'll try
to, just on a regular basis,

13
00:00:43,200 --> 00:00:46,560
every Thursday evening, have
them publish on the website

14
00:00:46,560 --> 00:00:50,560
so that you can download
them and annotate.

15
00:00:50,560 --> 00:00:51,440
Cool.

16
00:00:51,440 --> 00:00:54,360
So with that, let's start.

17
00:00:54,360 --> 00:01:01,600
And as usual, we're going to
recap last week's episodes.

18
00:01:01,600 --> 00:01:05,080
So if you remember,
lecture 1 and lecture 2

19
00:01:05,080 --> 00:01:09,920
were all about introducing
the concept of self-attention

20
00:01:09,920 --> 00:01:14,200
and linking them to the
construct of the transformer.

21
00:01:14,200 --> 00:01:19,400
And what we did last lecture was
look at all the types of models

22
00:01:19,400 --> 00:01:22,320
that are out there
and how they were all

23
00:01:22,320 --> 00:01:25,040
based on the transformer.

24
00:01:25,040 --> 00:01:29,200
So there are three categories,
three main categories of models.

25
00:01:29,200 --> 00:01:34,400
So the first one that we saw
was encoder-decoder model,

26
00:01:34,400 --> 00:01:37,417
which basically relies
on the transformer.

27
00:01:37,417 --> 00:01:39,000
It has the encoder
of the transformer,

28
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:41,000
the decoder of the transformer.

29
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:44,820
And typically, the tasks
there are input text.

30
00:01:44,820 --> 00:01:48,200
So text in, text out.

31
00:01:48,200 --> 00:01:52,746
So we saw that one example
was T5 and all the variations.

32
00:01:55,360 --> 00:01:58,440
The second type
of model is where

33
00:01:58,440 --> 00:02:02,000
we remove the decoder
from the transformer

34
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:06,760
and we obtain an
encoder-only model.

35
00:02:06,760 --> 00:02:10,759
So we went deeper
into BERT, which is

36
00:02:10,759 --> 00:02:13,440
the typical encoder-only model.

37
00:02:13,440 --> 00:02:16,160
And I guess, we
also saw that what

38
00:02:16,160 --> 00:02:20,200
BERT has is this nice
property that it's encoded

39
00:02:20,200 --> 00:02:24,840
embeddings are very meaningful
and expressive of the inputs.

40
00:02:24,840 --> 00:02:28,720
And so we saw the example
of classification,

41
00:02:28,720 --> 00:02:29,980
sentiment extraction.

42
00:02:29,980 --> 00:02:33,800
So what we did
was, in particular,

43
00:02:33,800 --> 00:02:36,320
take into consideration
the encoded embedding

44
00:02:36,320 --> 00:02:39,560
of the CLS token.

45
00:02:39,560 --> 00:02:45,160
So I guess in real life, BERT
is used to encode documents

46
00:02:45,160 --> 00:02:47,080
to encode sentences.

47
00:02:47,080 --> 00:02:49,720
And we're going to
see later in the class

48
00:02:49,720 --> 00:02:53,960
how these models are useful.

49
00:02:53,960 --> 00:02:57,270
And then last but
not least, we have

50
00:02:57,270 --> 00:03:02,350
the third category of models,
which is decoder only.

51
00:03:02,350 --> 00:03:06,630
So we only keep the decoder
part of the transformer.

52
00:03:06,630 --> 00:03:10,250
And so here, we also do a
little bit of a modification.

53
00:03:10,250 --> 00:03:12,950
So we remove the
cross-attention because we

54
00:03:12,950 --> 00:03:13,890
don't need it anymore.

55
00:03:13,890 --> 00:03:15,550
We don't have an encoder.

56
00:03:15,550 --> 00:03:22,790
And these kinds of models
are text in, text out.

57
00:03:22,790 --> 00:03:26,190
And so GPT is a very good
example of such models.

58
00:03:26,190 --> 00:03:30,920
And actually, most models these
days, they're decoder-only.

59
00:03:33,630 --> 00:03:36,270
So these are the
three main kinds

60
00:03:36,270 --> 00:03:39,990
of models that you
can see out there.

61
00:03:39,990 --> 00:03:43,590
So far so good for everyone?

62
00:03:43,590 --> 00:03:44,470
Cool.

63
00:03:44,470 --> 00:03:49,510
So with that, I'm going
to introduce the term LLM.

64
00:03:49,510 --> 00:03:54,590
So LLM stands for
large language model.

65
00:03:54,590 --> 00:03:56,950
So what is a large
language model?

66
00:03:56,950 --> 00:03:59,550
So first of all, a
large language model

67
00:03:59,550 --> 00:04:01,070
is a language model.

68
00:04:01,070 --> 00:04:05,870
So a language model is a
model that assigns probability

69
00:04:05,870 --> 00:04:08,710
to sequences of tokens.

70
00:04:08,710 --> 00:04:11,430
So in this case,
our model always

71
00:04:11,430 --> 00:04:15,550
predicts the probability
of the next token.

72
00:04:15,550 --> 00:04:20,390
So it's, in that sense,
a language model.

73
00:04:20,390 --> 00:04:22,950
But also, a large
language model is large.

74
00:04:22,950 --> 00:04:24,550
So why is it large?

75
00:04:24,550 --> 00:04:27,470
So we're going to see
that these models,

76
00:04:27,470 --> 00:04:31,350
they are actually scaled
up in terms of size.

77
00:04:31,350 --> 00:04:34,710
So first of all in
terms of model size.

78
00:04:34,710 --> 00:04:37,950
So these days, it's not
uncommon to see models

79
00:04:37,950 --> 00:04:42,750
on the order of hundreds
of billions of parameters.

80
00:04:42,750 --> 00:04:44,910
But typically,
when we say LLM we

81
00:04:44,910 --> 00:04:48,790
say at least on the
order of a billion.

82
00:04:48,790 --> 00:04:53,310
These models, they've also been
trained on a huge amount of data

83
00:04:53,310 --> 00:04:56,510
and hereby amount of
data, we quantify that

84
00:04:56,510 --> 00:05:00,310
by the number of tokens that
they were pre-trained with.

85
00:05:00,310 --> 00:05:02,270
And this is on the
order of magnitude

86
00:05:02,270 --> 00:05:04,990
of hundreds of
billions of tokens

87
00:05:04,990 --> 00:05:08,950
or even trillions of tokens.

88
00:05:08,950 --> 00:05:12,030
So I think the biggest ones are
like on the tens of trillions

89
00:05:12,030 --> 00:05:12,610
of tokens.

90
00:05:12,610 --> 00:05:17,150
So huge training sets.

91
00:05:17,150 --> 00:05:20,510
And they're also large because
they need a lot of compute.

92
00:05:20,510 --> 00:05:24,350
So typically you need a bunch
of GPUs to make them work.

93
00:05:24,350 --> 00:05:28,030
Although these days there's
been a lot of optimizations

94
00:05:28,030 --> 00:05:32,910
to have them work on
consumer based GPUs.

95
00:05:32,910 --> 00:05:35,950
So we're going to
see that later on.

96
00:05:35,950 --> 00:05:41,562
But in LLM is large according
to these categories.

97
00:05:41,562 --> 00:05:43,270
So another thing that
I want to point out

98
00:05:43,270 --> 00:05:47,830
is that all these terminologies,
they're relatively new.

99
00:05:47,830 --> 00:05:53,510
So I remember in
2018, '19, there was

100
00:05:53,510 --> 00:05:55,170
no real definition of an LLM.

101
00:05:55,170 --> 00:05:57,350
I think no one actually
talked about LLMs.

102
00:05:57,350 --> 00:06:00,110
In the beginning, maybe
people talked about LLMs.

103
00:06:00,110 --> 00:06:02,790
They included BERT.

104
00:06:02,790 --> 00:06:04,590
But Bert is an
encoder-only model

105
00:06:04,590 --> 00:06:06,750
that does not produce text.

106
00:06:06,750 --> 00:06:09,570
So with the current
definition of an LLM,

107
00:06:09,570 --> 00:06:12,950
which right now has been
pretty well established,

108
00:06:12,950 --> 00:06:18,710
BERT would not be an LLM
because it doesn't produce text.

109
00:06:18,710 --> 00:06:22,150
So here, we only
consider language models

110
00:06:22,150 --> 00:06:27,230
that do text to text, that are
very large in size, in terms

111
00:06:27,230 --> 00:06:29,590
of amount of data that have
been trained on and in terms

112
00:06:29,590 --> 00:06:32,430
of compute.

113
00:06:32,430 --> 00:06:33,430
Cool.

114
00:06:33,430 --> 00:06:38,590
And as we saw before, these
models are decoder-only.

115
00:06:38,590 --> 00:06:41,930
So here, what we do is
we remove the encoder,

116
00:06:41,930 --> 00:06:46,230
we only keep the
masked self-attention,

117
00:06:46,230 --> 00:06:49,510
the feedforward neural
network, and then the addition

118
00:06:49,510 --> 00:06:51,790
and normalization.

119
00:06:51,790 --> 00:06:53,750
So we only keep this.

120
00:06:53,750 --> 00:06:59,150
And this is the
backbone of LLMs.

121
00:06:59,150 --> 00:07:03,450
And so I mentioned GPT is
kind of a good example.

122
00:07:03,450 --> 00:07:04,470
But it's not just that.

123
00:07:04,470 --> 00:07:06,250
You have plenty of other models.

124
00:07:06,250 --> 00:07:09,590
So you may have heard of
LLaMA from Meta, Gemma

125
00:07:09,590 --> 00:07:14,300
from Google, DeepSeek,
Mistral, Qwen, and so on.

126
00:07:14,300 --> 00:07:16,790
The list is long.

127
00:07:16,790 --> 00:07:18,870
I would say roughly--

128
00:07:18,870 --> 00:07:23,530
I mean, more than 90%
of modern day LLMs,

129
00:07:23,530 --> 00:07:26,110
they're all decoder-only.

130
00:07:26,110 --> 00:07:30,470
So I think that's
something to keep in mind.

131
00:07:30,470 --> 00:07:33,110
Cool.

132
00:07:33,110 --> 00:07:33,610
OK.

133
00:07:33,610 --> 00:07:37,750
So now you how LLMs are made of.

134
00:07:37,750 --> 00:07:41,670
But there is something else
that people these days also

135
00:07:41,670 --> 00:07:43,370
introduce to these models.

136
00:07:43,370 --> 00:07:46,750
And we're going to
see that in a bit.

137
00:07:46,750 --> 00:07:49,550
So I mentioned that
these models are

138
00:07:49,550 --> 00:07:54,070
huge in size, again,
typically hundreds of billions

139
00:07:54,070 --> 00:07:55,630
of parameters.

140
00:07:55,630 --> 00:08:02,310
So it takes a lot of compute
to just compute one inference,

141
00:08:02,310 --> 00:08:05,390
or also to train these models.

142
00:08:05,390 --> 00:08:08,070
But you may wonder,
do you really

143
00:08:08,070 --> 00:08:11,910
need to have all
these parameters be

144
00:08:11,910 --> 00:08:17,950
activated during a forward pass,
to make a simple prediction?

145
00:08:17,950 --> 00:08:21,870
So I'm going to have
a little metaphor.

146
00:08:21,870 --> 00:08:24,590
So let's suppose
you enter in a room.

147
00:08:24,590 --> 00:08:30,430
And in the room, there is a
mathematician, a physicist,

148
00:08:30,430 --> 00:08:33,590
a chemist and a historian.

149
00:08:33,590 --> 00:08:35,150
So you come in
this class, there's

150
00:08:35,150 --> 00:08:38,990
a bunch of people who are
expert in what they do.

151
00:08:38,990 --> 00:08:43,630
And you have a question,
you have a math question.

152
00:08:43,630 --> 00:08:49,100
So a question I have for you is,
who would you ask your question?

153
00:08:49,100 --> 00:08:50,480
Would you ask the mathematician?

154
00:08:50,480 --> 00:08:51,563
Would you ask the chemist?

155
00:08:51,563 --> 00:08:53,940
Would you ask everyone?

156
00:08:53,940 --> 00:08:56,380
Well, right now,
we ask everyone.

157
00:08:56,380 --> 00:08:58,460
We ask all parameters
of the model

158
00:08:58,460 --> 00:09:06,260
to be involved in the
computation of the generation.

159
00:09:06,260 --> 00:09:11,500
And so the idea here
is given an input,

160
00:09:11,500 --> 00:09:15,340
maybe it's not necessary
to ask everyone

161
00:09:15,340 --> 00:09:17,980
to be involved in
the computation.

162
00:09:17,980 --> 00:09:23,460
So the idea is let's actually
just have a subset of the model

163
00:09:23,460 --> 00:09:27,410
be involved in the
computation of the next token.

164
00:09:30,500 --> 00:09:34,900
So I'm just introducing
this idea of experts.

165
00:09:34,900 --> 00:09:37,220
So let's suppose
we're introducing

166
00:09:37,220 --> 00:09:38,700
the following notation.

167
00:09:38,700 --> 00:09:42,220
So let's suppose
we have n experts.

168
00:09:42,220 --> 00:09:45,960
So think of it as your
mathematician, your chemist,

169
00:09:45,960 --> 00:09:48,460
historian, whatever.

170
00:09:48,460 --> 00:09:50,500
So these are your experts.

171
00:09:50,500 --> 00:09:59,340
And the idea is given an input
x, you're going to ask yourself

172
00:09:59,340 --> 00:10:05,780
who should be involved in the
generation of the outputs.

173
00:10:05,780 --> 00:10:09,980
So you're going to have,
let's say, another network.

174
00:10:09,980 --> 00:10:13,460
Where we're going to
call it G like gates,

175
00:10:13,460 --> 00:10:16,740
but it's also sometimes
called router.

176
00:10:16,740 --> 00:10:21,740
So let's suppose we have
some gates that tells us

177
00:10:21,740 --> 00:10:28,540
which experts should be
involved in the inference.

178
00:10:28,540 --> 00:10:30,300
So if we have that,
so let's suppose here,

179
00:10:30,300 --> 00:10:33,340
the gate tells us OK, so
actually, expert number 2

180
00:10:33,340 --> 00:10:37,020
is well suited to
answer your question.

181
00:10:37,020 --> 00:10:40,260
So here, the idea is
that the input is just

182
00:10:40,260 --> 00:10:48,500
going to flow into that expert,
but not the other experts.

183
00:10:48,500 --> 00:10:51,300
So this has a name.

184
00:10:51,300 --> 00:10:53,900
It's called mixture of experts.

185
00:10:53,900 --> 00:10:56,380
So it's denoted MoE.

186
00:10:56,380 --> 00:10:57,760
Everyone talks about MoE.

187
00:10:57,760 --> 00:10:59,740
So these are a
mixture of experts.

188
00:10:59,740 --> 00:11:05,700
And so the formula that you
will see a lot is this one.

189
00:11:05,700 --> 00:11:09,740
So the output y,
which is denoted y hat

190
00:11:09,740 --> 00:11:18,980
is the sum of the expert output
weighted by some quantity, which

191
00:11:18,980 --> 00:11:22,260
is the output of the
gate, which tells you

192
00:11:22,260 --> 00:11:27,640
how important the output
of each expert is.

193
00:11:27,640 --> 00:11:28,140
Yeah.

194
00:11:37,855 --> 00:11:38,480
Great question.

195
00:11:38,480 --> 00:11:40,125
So the question is,
how do you train G?

196
00:11:40,125 --> 00:11:41,500
How do you train
E. So typically,

197
00:11:41,500 --> 00:11:44,620
you train them jointly.

198
00:11:44,620 --> 00:11:47,920
So we're going to see that
maybe in a little later.

199
00:11:47,920 --> 00:11:51,700
But you can think of it
as just training as usual.

200
00:11:51,700 --> 00:11:53,900
You do your forward pass,
you compute the loss

201
00:11:53,900 --> 00:11:56,260
and you backprop.

202
00:11:56,260 --> 00:11:58,100
And it's actually an
interesting question

203
00:11:58,100 --> 00:12:01,220
because there is some challenges
that come with training MoEs

204
00:12:01,220 --> 00:12:03,600
that we're going
to see in a second.

205
00:12:03,600 --> 00:12:04,100
Yeah.

206
00:12:09,820 --> 00:12:12,377
Question is, what are these E's.

207
00:12:12,377 --> 00:12:13,960
What is the architecture
of these E's?

208
00:12:13,960 --> 00:12:16,540
So let's suppose right now
that there's just some network.

209
00:12:16,540 --> 00:12:18,120
We're not specifying
them for now,

210
00:12:18,120 --> 00:12:20,180
but we're going to
see this in a second.

211
00:12:20,180 --> 00:12:24,140
Let's suppose for now,
it's some network.

212
00:12:24,140 --> 00:12:26,060
Cool.

213
00:12:26,060 --> 00:12:26,900
OK.

214
00:12:26,900 --> 00:12:31,120
So I told you that what if
we don't activate everyone.

215
00:12:31,120 --> 00:12:32,440
What if we activate a subset?

216
00:12:32,440 --> 00:12:38,340
But this formula,
actually, I guess,

217
00:12:38,340 --> 00:12:43,020
assumes that we're actually
considering all expert outputs.

218
00:12:43,020 --> 00:12:48,140
So I just want to distinguish
two kinds of MoEs.

219
00:12:48,140 --> 00:12:52,420
So there's one kind that
is called a dense MoE.

220
00:12:52,420 --> 00:12:56,140
So a dense MoE
actually does not have

221
00:12:56,140 --> 00:13:00,700
any constraints on the number
of experts that are involved.

222
00:13:00,700 --> 00:13:05,280
So these weights, they can
be anywhere between 0 and 1.

223
00:13:05,280 --> 00:13:09,540
So think of them as a
probability distribution.

224
00:13:09,540 --> 00:13:15,340
But it's just going to put more
weight towards some experts

225
00:13:15,340 --> 00:13:17,615
compared to others.

226
00:13:17,615 --> 00:13:19,740
So back to the example that
I had, so let's suppose

227
00:13:19,740 --> 00:13:22,940
I have a math question.

228
00:13:22,940 --> 00:13:24,800
So I'm going to ask
the mathematician,

229
00:13:24,800 --> 00:13:26,680
the chemist, the historian.

230
00:13:26,680 --> 00:13:30,020
So I'm probably going
to add a higher weight

231
00:13:30,020 --> 00:13:31,780
to what the mathematician
says compared

232
00:13:31,780 --> 00:13:33,700
to let's say, the historian.

233
00:13:33,700 --> 00:13:36,570
So this is the idea.

234
00:13:36,570 --> 00:13:40,570
But then the
interesting thing is

235
00:13:40,570 --> 00:13:44,810
when we constrain
the number of experts

236
00:13:44,810 --> 00:13:47,530
that are activated,
because here,

237
00:13:47,530 --> 00:13:50,290
as we mentioned
previously, what we're

238
00:13:50,290 --> 00:13:53,090
interested in is to
not involve everyone

239
00:13:53,090 --> 00:13:58,530
is to make some savings in the
amount of compute that we do.

240
00:13:58,530 --> 00:14:04,050
So there's a second kind of MoE
that's called the sparse MoE.

241
00:14:04,050 --> 00:14:08,810
And what it does is it only
selects the quote unquote,

242
00:14:08,810 --> 00:14:12,650
"top k" experts.

243
00:14:12,650 --> 00:14:14,710
So k can be equal to 1.

244
00:14:14,710 --> 00:14:16,890
So one expert or even two.

245
00:14:16,890 --> 00:14:19,170
So it's a hyperparameter
that you choose.

246
00:14:19,170 --> 00:14:22,450
And so here, the
expression of the output

247
00:14:22,450 --> 00:14:28,330
becomes the sum over
all the chosen experts

248
00:14:28,330 --> 00:14:32,710
of a G of x times E of x.

249
00:14:36,770 --> 00:14:39,570
So far, so good?

250
00:14:39,570 --> 00:14:40,490
Cool.

251
00:14:40,490 --> 00:14:42,670
And of course, there's
a lot more to it.

252
00:14:42,670 --> 00:14:45,330
So in case you are
interested in learning more,

253
00:14:45,330 --> 00:14:46,970
feel free to go into
the resources that

254
00:14:46,970 --> 00:14:49,690
are at the bottom of the slide.

255
00:14:49,690 --> 00:14:52,570
So one thing that I
will say is that we

256
00:14:52,570 --> 00:14:56,570
have a unit of measure
of the amount of compute

257
00:14:56,570 --> 00:15:00,890
that these models
produce for each pass.

258
00:15:00,890 --> 00:15:05,330
So you will see the term FLOPS.

259
00:15:05,330 --> 00:15:09,250
So have you seen the
term FLOPS out there?

260
00:15:09,250 --> 00:15:10,210
No, not really.

261
00:15:10,210 --> 00:15:15,610
So it stands for
floating-point operations.

262
00:15:15,610 --> 00:15:18,930
So it quantifies
how many operations.

263
00:15:18,930 --> 00:15:22,370
Think of it as additions,
multiplications

264
00:15:22,370 --> 00:15:26,690
are involved in a
forward pass let's say.

265
00:15:26,690 --> 00:15:33,810
And it basically quantifies
how compute heavy is your task.

266
00:15:33,810 --> 00:15:36,610
So typically, what
we say is when

267
00:15:36,610 --> 00:15:40,450
we go through a sparse MoE
as opposed to a dense Moe,

268
00:15:40,450 --> 00:15:44,730
we have a lower amount of FLOPS.

269
00:15:44,730 --> 00:15:48,050
So this is the unit of
measure that you will see.

270
00:15:48,050 --> 00:15:53,330
But back to your question,
so what are these experts?

271
00:15:53,330 --> 00:15:59,370
So if you remember, I mean, 10
minutes ago, we said that LLMs,

272
00:15:59,370 --> 00:16:02,570
they are decoder-only models.

273
00:16:02,570 --> 00:16:04,970
So I have a question for you.

274
00:16:04,970 --> 00:16:11,130
Let's suppose we wanted to
put some MoEs in our LLM.

275
00:16:11,130 --> 00:16:13,930
Where would we put it?

276
00:16:13,930 --> 00:16:16,330
So here, I guess, we
have three choices.

277
00:16:16,330 --> 00:16:19,330
We have the masked
self-attention layer.

278
00:16:19,330 --> 00:16:22,110
We have the feedforward
neural network.

279
00:16:22,110 --> 00:16:23,790
And then we have
this normalization.

280
00:16:23,790 --> 00:16:27,430
So question for you, I guess,
where would you put this?

281
00:16:32,770 --> 00:16:37,290
I guess, where do you think is--

282
00:16:37,290 --> 00:16:40,390
I guess, the most complex
parts of the network.

283
00:16:40,390 --> 00:16:44,970
Where is there a
lot of operations?

284
00:16:44,970 --> 00:16:45,970
Feedforward?

285
00:16:45,970 --> 00:16:46,770
Yes.

286
00:16:46,770 --> 00:16:47,390
Yeah.

287
00:16:47,390 --> 00:16:48,030
Great answer.

288
00:16:48,030 --> 00:16:51,970
So it's indeed the
feedforward neural network.

289
00:16:51,970 --> 00:16:55,490
And the reason for that is I
think Shervin mentioned it,

290
00:16:55,490 --> 00:16:57,850
I think, in lecture 1.

291
00:16:57,850 --> 00:17:01,410
So if you remember, the
feedforward neural network

292
00:17:01,410 --> 00:17:05,730
is a network such that
you have the input, which

293
00:17:05,730 --> 00:17:10,890
is your D-dimensional
input vector.

294
00:17:10,890 --> 00:17:15,010
And then you have this being
projected into, let's say,

295
00:17:15,010 --> 00:17:17,750
a DFF dimensional space.

296
00:17:17,750 --> 00:17:23,210
And then it goes back to the
D-dimensional, I guess, space.

297
00:17:23,210 --> 00:17:32,410
So the DFF is typically larger
than your dimension of, I guess,

298
00:17:32,410 --> 00:17:33,570
the inputs.

299
00:17:33,570 --> 00:17:35,450
When I say input, it's here.

300
00:17:35,450 --> 00:17:37,110
So it's typically larger.

301
00:17:37,110 --> 00:17:41,290
So the amount of
parameters that you

302
00:17:41,290 --> 00:17:44,130
have in that feedforward
neural network

303
00:17:44,130 --> 00:17:48,970
is something on the order of
magnitude of D model times

304
00:17:48,970 --> 00:17:52,770
DFF times 2 plus some bias.

305
00:17:52,770 --> 00:17:55,090
So it's basically your
order of magnitude.

306
00:17:55,090 --> 00:18:00,230
And the attention
layer, if you remember,

307
00:18:00,230 --> 00:18:05,148
it's basically composed of
the projection matrices,

308
00:18:05,148 --> 00:18:07,190
what is the dimension of
the projection matrices.

309
00:18:07,190 --> 00:18:10,650
So it's D model
times the dimension

310
00:18:10,650 --> 00:18:15,530
of keys to dimension of queries
the dimension of values.

311
00:18:15,530 --> 00:18:19,570
And this dimension is
typically much lower.

312
00:18:19,570 --> 00:18:22,370
So think of it over 100.

313
00:18:22,370 --> 00:18:26,730
So your D model is typically
O over 100, O over 1,000.

314
00:18:26,730 --> 00:18:32,220
And then the projection here,
the DFF is O over 1,000,

315
00:18:32,220 --> 00:18:36,360
O over 10,000.

316
00:18:36,360 --> 00:18:36,860
Cool.

317
00:18:36,860 --> 00:18:39,520
So is everyone now
convinced that this

318
00:18:39,520 --> 00:18:44,800
is a good way, good place to
put the mixture of experts?

319
00:18:44,800 --> 00:18:47,280
Yeah?

320
00:18:47,280 --> 00:18:47,820
Cool.

321
00:18:47,820 --> 00:18:50,760
So this is actually
how it's done.

322
00:18:50,760 --> 00:18:58,760
So in modern day LLMs, this
idea of not involving everyone

323
00:18:58,760 --> 00:19:02,600
in the computation of
the next token prediction

324
00:19:02,600 --> 00:19:07,520
is such that you would
put the mixture of experts

325
00:19:07,520 --> 00:19:12,040
where the fn is
just basically here.

326
00:19:12,040 --> 00:19:18,290
And typically you would have
a sparse mixture of experts.

327
00:19:18,290 --> 00:19:20,040
So back to your question,
so these experts

328
00:19:20,040 --> 00:19:22,520
are actually feedforward
neural network.

329
00:19:22,520 --> 00:19:26,960
So you would have several
networks that you can train,

330
00:19:26,960 --> 00:19:29,450
but you would only activate one.

331
00:19:32,440 --> 00:19:34,260
So typically, k
would be equal to 1.

332
00:19:34,260 --> 00:19:36,900
It can be also equal to 2 but
it would only be a subset.

333
00:19:36,900 --> 00:19:39,680
So that's my point.

334
00:19:39,680 --> 00:19:46,240
And this routing would be
done at the token level.

335
00:19:46,240 --> 00:19:48,840
So if you remember, the
decoder, it basically

336
00:19:48,840 --> 00:19:51,500
takes something as inputs.

337
00:19:51,500 --> 00:19:54,400
So a bunch of tokens.

338
00:19:54,400 --> 00:19:58,480
And here, what I'm
saying is that each token

339
00:19:58,480 --> 00:20:01,800
will be processed by
an expert that may be

340
00:20:01,800 --> 00:20:05,400
different from the other token.

341
00:20:05,400 --> 00:20:11,840
So the router here would take
the representation of the token

342
00:20:11,840 --> 00:20:17,000
as input and figure out
which expert should be best

343
00:20:17,000 --> 00:20:21,520
for this token to flow towards.

344
00:20:21,520 --> 00:20:25,200
Does this idea make sense?

345
00:20:25,200 --> 00:20:28,200
So I have a little
illustration later

346
00:20:28,200 --> 00:20:31,880
on that hopefully will help.

347
00:20:31,880 --> 00:20:34,860
So now back to your question
about how you train this model.

348
00:20:34,860 --> 00:20:36,820
Do you train the
router separately?

349
00:20:36,820 --> 00:20:38,920
Do you train the
experts separately?

350
00:20:38,920 --> 00:20:42,880
So one challenge
that people have

351
00:20:42,880 --> 00:20:48,840
is when they train these
MoE-based models, to make sure

352
00:20:48,840 --> 00:20:56,920
that all experts are, I guess,
having a weight, are being used.

353
00:20:56,920 --> 00:21:00,840
Because it's very possible
that you train your model

354
00:21:00,840 --> 00:21:03,680
and that somehow
only, I don't know,

355
00:21:03,680 --> 00:21:07,160
one or two experts
always get activated.

356
00:21:07,160 --> 00:21:09,860
And the other one, they
always are inactive.

357
00:21:09,860 --> 00:21:13,680
They are never involved
in the computation.

358
00:21:13,680 --> 00:21:17,440
So this problem is
called routing collapse.

359
00:21:17,440 --> 00:21:19,400
So why is it called
routing collapse?

360
00:21:19,400 --> 00:21:23,240
It's because the
router always chooses

361
00:21:23,240 --> 00:21:27,600
some experts, but not others.

362
00:21:27,600 --> 00:21:29,600
So this is a challenge.

363
00:21:29,600 --> 00:21:32,840
And the way people
try to mitigate

364
00:21:32,840 --> 00:21:37,840
this challenge is by
changing the loss function

365
00:21:37,840 --> 00:21:42,800
and adding it some extra
term, which is written here.

366
00:21:42,800 --> 00:21:47,480
So it's basically some
hyperparameter alpha times

367
00:21:47,480 --> 00:21:54,760
the number of experts
times the sum of quantities

368
00:21:54,760 --> 00:21:58,680
that depend on
whether or not tokens

369
00:21:58,680 --> 00:22:01,880
went to a certain expert's
eye, and then summed

370
00:22:01,880 --> 00:22:04,160
over all experts.

371
00:22:04,160 --> 00:22:08,080
So it's not super important
that you completely understand

372
00:22:08,080 --> 00:22:11,840
exactly how that formula works.

373
00:22:11,840 --> 00:22:15,280
The only thing that I think you
should take away from this slide

374
00:22:15,280 --> 00:22:23,960
is that this extra loss allows
these quantities to converge

375
00:22:23,960 --> 00:22:27,360
more towards uniform
distributions.

376
00:22:27,360 --> 00:22:29,600
So what are these quantities,
just as a reminder.

377
00:22:29,600 --> 00:22:34,160
So f of I is the
fraction of tokens

378
00:22:34,160 --> 00:22:40,080
that are routed to
expert I. And P of I

379
00:22:40,080 --> 00:22:45,160
is the average routing
probability for expert I.

380
00:22:45,160 --> 00:22:51,680
So when I say that all experts
should be used the same, what

381
00:22:51,680 --> 00:22:54,320
I'm saying is I want
this probability to be

382
00:22:54,320 --> 00:22:59,860
kind of uniform across experts.

383
00:22:59,860 --> 00:23:00,360
Yeah.

384
00:23:20,200 --> 00:23:22,727
So the question
is, I guess, when

385
00:23:22,727 --> 00:23:24,060
do you compute these quantities?

386
00:23:24,060 --> 00:23:28,060
So yeah, you can think of it
as a regular training process.

387
00:23:28,060 --> 00:23:33,440
You do some mini batch,
you go through the model

388
00:23:33,440 --> 00:23:35,520
and then you compute
all these quantities.

389
00:23:35,520 --> 00:23:39,880
And then what you do is
you do your backpropagation

390
00:23:39,880 --> 00:23:41,800
based on that.

391
00:23:41,800 --> 00:23:43,680
And I guess what I
want you to remember

392
00:23:43,680 --> 00:23:50,480
is that this incentivizes
the probability,

393
00:23:50,480 --> 00:23:53,520
I guess, the choice
of the writer

394
00:23:53,520 --> 00:23:56,280
to be more uniform
across experts,

395
00:23:56,280 --> 00:24:02,000
which is something that
mitigates this routing collapse

396
00:24:02,000 --> 00:24:02,860
phenomenon.

397
00:24:05,740 --> 00:24:06,240
Yeah.

398
00:24:14,275 --> 00:24:15,900
So the question is,
can we use Dropout?

399
00:24:15,900 --> 00:24:16,400
Of course.

400
00:24:16,400 --> 00:24:18,970
You can always bundle that
with some other techniques.

401
00:24:18,970 --> 00:24:22,510
So people have just kind of
found this to be very helpful.

402
00:24:22,510 --> 00:24:24,270
So speaking of other
techniques, there

403
00:24:24,270 --> 00:24:25,937
is something that
I've not talked about,

404
00:24:25,937 --> 00:24:28,870
which is very similar
to the Dropout idea.

405
00:24:28,870 --> 00:24:32,590
So it's called noisy gating.

406
00:24:32,590 --> 00:24:41,030
Noisy gating is basically
you have your predictions

407
00:24:41,030 --> 00:24:45,830
from the gates, but then
you add some noise to it.

408
00:24:45,830 --> 00:24:48,410
So basically, it's
by pure chance,

409
00:24:48,410 --> 00:24:51,793
it just allows other experts to
be involved in the computation.

410
00:24:51,793 --> 00:24:53,210
So it's also some
other technique.

411
00:24:53,210 --> 00:24:54,460
There's a bunch of techniques.

412
00:24:54,460 --> 00:24:57,550
But yeah, Dropout is indeed
quite useful for things

413
00:24:57,550 --> 00:24:58,490
like overfitting.

414
00:24:58,490 --> 00:25:04,110
And the idea can be reused
in different settings.

415
00:25:04,110 --> 00:25:06,240
Yep.

416
00:25:06,240 --> 00:25:06,740
Yep.

417
00:25:13,990 --> 00:25:15,790
So the question
is, how can you--

418
00:25:15,790 --> 00:25:18,670
so do you mean differentiable?

419
00:25:18,670 --> 00:25:21,490
So here, I guess, how do
you take the derivative.

420
00:25:21,490 --> 00:25:23,950
Is that your question?

421
00:25:23,950 --> 00:25:26,390
How is the derivative--
can you explain a bit more

422
00:25:26,390 --> 00:25:28,130
what your concern is?

423
00:25:43,750 --> 00:25:50,630
So I guess, to this question, so
the average routing probability.

424
00:25:50,630 --> 00:25:58,270
So that one is a function
of the gate output.

425
00:25:58,270 --> 00:25:59,910
That's one.

426
00:25:59,910 --> 00:26:02,290
PI.

427
00:26:02,290 --> 00:26:05,390
So I guess, your
question is for FI.

428
00:26:05,390 --> 00:26:07,850
For FI, OK.

429
00:26:07,850 --> 00:26:10,370
I don't have a good
answer on top of my head,

430
00:26:10,370 --> 00:26:12,510
but I think people
have some techniques.

431
00:26:12,510 --> 00:26:15,650
And these days, you just don't
even have to do this by hand.

432
00:26:15,650 --> 00:26:18,990
You have the built in thing.

433
00:26:18,990 --> 00:26:20,850
So maybe I can follow
up with you for FI.

434
00:26:20,850 --> 00:26:24,810
But for P of I, do you see
that this one is quite clean.

435
00:26:24,810 --> 00:26:29,600
It's just the average of the
probabilities from the gates.

436
00:26:35,850 --> 00:26:36,350
Yeah.

437
00:26:36,350 --> 00:26:38,270
So basically the probability--

438
00:26:38,270 --> 00:26:40,450
the output probability
from the gate,

439
00:26:40,450 --> 00:26:45,270
you can think of it as just
the vector being projected

440
00:26:45,270 --> 00:26:48,430
on a space of n,
where n corresponds

441
00:26:48,430 --> 00:26:51,270
to your number of experts.

442
00:26:51,270 --> 00:26:53,250
And then it's gone
through Softmax.

443
00:26:53,250 --> 00:26:57,270
So your output is basically
summing up to one.

444
00:26:57,270 --> 00:27:01,430
And each of these
dimensions, they

445
00:27:01,430 --> 00:27:04,230
represent the
value corresponding

446
00:27:04,230 --> 00:27:08,170
to what expert I would
be, I guess, used for.

447
00:27:08,170 --> 00:27:11,110
For instance, the first
dimension would be for expert 1,

448
00:27:11,110 --> 00:27:13,885
second dimension would be
for expert 2, and so on.

449
00:27:13,885 --> 00:27:16,010
So you just take the average
of this, and this one,

450
00:27:16,010 --> 00:27:18,250
you can express it from
all the parameters.

451
00:27:18,250 --> 00:27:21,370
So I think you should
be fine with that one.

452
00:27:21,370 --> 00:27:21,870
Yeah.

453
00:27:31,390 --> 00:27:34,850
So the question is if we
increase the number of MoEs,

454
00:27:34,850 --> 00:27:37,170
does it increase the
number of model parameters?

455
00:27:37,170 --> 00:27:38,710
So it's a great question.

456
00:27:38,710 --> 00:27:43,470
So it's actually one of the
ideas behind MoE-based models,

457
00:27:43,470 --> 00:27:47,350
which is that you can scale
the model without having

458
00:27:47,350 --> 00:27:51,830
to incur the cost of having
significantly more compute

459
00:27:51,830 --> 00:27:54,030
at inference time.

460
00:27:54,030 --> 00:27:56,390
So you can increase--
so people say capacity.

461
00:27:56,390 --> 00:27:59,390
Can increase the
capacity of your model,

462
00:27:59,390 --> 00:28:05,510
but you will still keep some,
I guess, like controlled amount

463
00:28:05,510 --> 00:28:08,210
of active parameters.

464
00:28:08,210 --> 00:28:10,790
And active parameters
are the parameters that

465
00:28:10,790 --> 00:28:13,230
are used for a forward pass.

466
00:28:13,230 --> 00:28:15,510
So yeah, people just use that.

467
00:28:15,510 --> 00:28:17,890
So yeah, it would just increase
the number of parameters.

468
00:28:17,890 --> 00:28:21,590
So that's why you see
some MoE-based models that

469
00:28:21,590 --> 00:28:24,230
are even bigger than
the ones that we

470
00:28:24,230 --> 00:28:26,730
had on the order of
hundreds of billions.

471
00:28:26,730 --> 00:28:30,290
We even have on the order
of trillions of parameters.

472
00:28:30,290 --> 00:28:33,870
So for instance here,
one reading I recommend

473
00:28:33,870 --> 00:28:39,150
is switch transformer,
which scaled up to one point

474
00:28:39,150 --> 00:28:41,510
something trillion parameters.

475
00:28:41,510 --> 00:28:44,710
So yeah, it's definitely more.

476
00:28:44,710 --> 00:28:47,590
But that being said, so
if you read the paper,

477
00:28:47,590 --> 00:28:50,230
you will also see that
these models, there

478
00:28:50,230 --> 00:28:53,750
are more what they
call sample efficient.

479
00:28:53,750 --> 00:28:59,110
So they take less time
to be as good as what

480
00:28:59,110 --> 00:29:03,510
the model would have been with
a lower number of parameters.

481
00:29:03,510 --> 00:29:09,100
So if you draw
the training curve

482
00:29:09,100 --> 00:29:11,260
as a function of
the training time,

483
00:29:11,260 --> 00:29:14,120
you see that these models are
typically more sample efficient.

484
00:29:18,040 --> 00:29:18,540
Sorry.

485
00:29:25,980 --> 00:29:26,480
Yeah.

486
00:29:26,480 --> 00:29:27,220
Yeah, exactly.

487
00:29:27,220 --> 00:29:28,600
Everything here is a trade off.

488
00:29:28,600 --> 00:29:30,580
Everything here is a trade off.

489
00:29:30,580 --> 00:29:31,540
Yeah.

490
00:29:31,540 --> 00:29:32,480
Cool.

491
00:29:32,480 --> 00:29:32,980
Yeah.

492
00:29:41,660 --> 00:29:43,780
So the question is,
each attention head

493
00:29:43,780 --> 00:29:45,440
will have a number of experts.

494
00:29:45,440 --> 00:29:48,420
So it's actually regardless
of the attention heads.

495
00:29:48,420 --> 00:29:50,300
So the attention heads,
you can think of them

496
00:29:50,300 --> 00:29:53,380
as being independent,
something else.

497
00:29:53,380 --> 00:29:56,360
And the number of experts
is independent of that.

498
00:29:59,500 --> 00:30:00,480
Does that make sense?

499
00:30:04,980 --> 00:30:07,845
Yeah.

500
00:30:07,845 --> 00:30:10,310
Right.

501
00:30:10,310 --> 00:30:11,000
All right.

502
00:30:11,000 --> 00:30:11,500
Yeah.

503
00:30:11,500 --> 00:30:14,780
The question is whether every
block will have a number.

504
00:30:14,780 --> 00:30:15,560
The answer is yes.

505
00:30:15,560 --> 00:30:18,900
And typically those
