01:15:17,260 --> 01:15:21,780
give examples of inputs
and outputs to the LLM

1257
01:15:21,780 --> 01:15:25,780
before asking the input
that you're interested in.

1258
01:15:25,780 --> 01:15:29,780
So in the case of a teddy
bears and a bedtime stories, so

1259
01:15:29,780 --> 01:15:32,040
you might name your teddy bears.

1260
01:15:32,040 --> 01:15:35,260
So maybe you have teddy
bear that's called Teddy.

1261
01:15:35,260 --> 01:15:37,080
And you generated a story.

1262
01:15:37,080 --> 01:15:39,500
So you put your query,
you put the story

1263
01:15:39,500 --> 01:15:43,650
that you want to generate, and
you give multiple such examples.

1264
01:15:43,650 --> 01:15:48,930
And let's say you have another
teddy bear that's called Bob.

1265
01:15:48,930 --> 01:15:51,410
And then you want to
generate a story for Bob.

1266
01:15:51,410 --> 01:15:53,230
So you put all of
these examples,

1267
01:15:53,230 --> 01:15:56,787
and you ask the LLM
to generate the story

1268
01:15:56,787 --> 01:15:57,870
that you're interested in.

1269
01:15:57,870 --> 01:16:01,880
And then this is basically what
we call a few-shots setting.

1270
01:16:04,390 --> 01:16:04,890
OK.

1271
01:16:04,890 --> 01:16:05,890
Great.

1272
01:16:05,890 --> 01:16:13,690
So now, generally, when
you look at the performance

1273
01:16:13,690 --> 01:16:17,090
of the resulting
task, giving examples

1274
01:16:17,090 --> 01:16:21,490
tends to steer the LLM
nicely into the task

1275
01:16:21,490 --> 01:16:22,890
that you're interested in.

1276
01:16:22,890 --> 01:16:26,490
Just because you
have given an idea

1277
01:16:26,490 --> 01:16:29,250
to the model of what
you are looking for.

1278
01:16:29,250 --> 01:16:32,730
And then it can use what it
has learned during its training

1279
01:16:32,730 --> 01:16:37,170
process to connect the dots
and basically replicates.

1280
01:16:39,980 --> 01:16:42,910
But of course, you need
to gather such examples.

1281
01:16:42,910 --> 01:16:44,490
So this is costly.

1282
01:16:44,490 --> 01:16:48,910
This will put some more
tokens in the context window.

1283
01:16:48,910 --> 01:16:52,370
So you will need
to more compute.

1284
01:16:52,370 --> 01:16:54,690
But there is an
interesting trade

1285
01:16:54,690 --> 01:16:57,730
off here that we see
in recent models.

1286
01:16:57,730 --> 01:17:01,450
So they are gaining more and
more reasoning capabilities,

1287
01:17:01,450 --> 01:17:07,270
which is why I put the
generally nuance in italic here.

1288
01:17:07,270 --> 01:17:11,770
So they are generally better,
few-shots, but not always.

1289
01:17:11,770 --> 01:17:14,810
Because these days, with
these better models,

1290
01:17:14,810 --> 01:17:20,770
people have seen that with
basically making the instruction

1291
01:17:20,770 --> 01:17:24,570
better, you could
make the performance

1292
01:17:24,570 --> 01:17:29,370
of in-context learning on
par, or even better than

1293
01:17:29,370 --> 01:17:33,370
if you provide examples, because
basically, when you think of it,

1294
01:17:33,370 --> 01:17:37,010
when you provide examples,
you constrain your model

1295
01:17:37,010 --> 01:17:40,170
into given sets of
examples that are finite.

1296
01:17:40,170 --> 01:17:42,370
So when you are
at inference time,

1297
01:17:42,370 --> 01:17:45,850
let's say, you want to perform
a task on a distribution of data

1298
01:17:45,850 --> 01:17:49,170
that has not been seen,
it is harder for the model

1299
01:17:49,170 --> 01:17:53,850
to generalize because it
will try to align on what

1300
01:17:53,850 --> 01:17:55,970
it has seen in the context.

1301
01:17:55,970 --> 01:17:59,970
Whereas if you turn your
instructions into something that

1302
01:17:59,970 --> 01:18:02,130
is more reasoning
based, you explain

1303
01:18:02,130 --> 01:18:05,550
how to do the task
with natural language,

1304
01:18:05,550 --> 01:18:09,350
it can use its reasoning
abilities to actually do it.

1305
01:18:09,350 --> 01:18:12,490
And this is something that you
see more and more these days.

1306
01:18:12,490 --> 01:18:16,750
So the literature on this, I
think, is still in progress,

1307
01:18:16,750 --> 01:18:19,570
but you have some
papers like a plan

1308
01:18:19,570 --> 01:18:23,550
and solve that's I
think came out recently.

1309
01:18:23,550 --> 01:18:27,090
And that shows if you ask the
LLM to plan itself and then

1310
01:18:27,090 --> 01:18:31,490
solve something, it can
have very good performance.

1311
01:18:31,490 --> 01:18:36,910
So yeah, this is an
interesting fact.

1312
01:18:36,910 --> 01:18:37,410
OK.

1313
01:18:37,410 --> 01:18:38,530
Great.

1314
01:18:38,530 --> 01:18:42,330
So now that we have seen
basically the kinds of learning

1315
01:18:42,330 --> 01:18:44,490
that we have, now,
we're going to see

1316
01:18:44,490 --> 01:18:48,730
what we can do to improve
the quality of the response.

1317
01:18:48,730 --> 01:18:51,890
So there is this concept
called chain of thought,

1318
01:18:51,890 --> 01:18:57,810
where researchers have seen that
if you force the model to come

1319
01:18:57,810 --> 01:19:00,690
up with some rationale
to some answer

1320
01:19:00,690 --> 01:19:05,130
before actually giving it, it
would give higher performance.

1321
01:19:05,130 --> 01:19:08,550
So this is what people
call as chain of thought.

1322
01:19:08,550 --> 01:19:11,730
It's basically what
led you to the answer.

1323
01:19:11,730 --> 01:19:16,250
So here, for example,
if you ask yourself,

1324
01:19:16,250 --> 01:19:18,570
how old is this teddy bear?

1325
01:19:18,570 --> 01:19:22,650
And if you force the model to
respond directly with a number,

1326
01:19:22,650 --> 01:19:26,330
it might not be able
to do the connection as

1327
01:19:26,330 --> 01:19:30,090
to exactly why the Teddy
bear is a given age.

1328
01:19:30,090 --> 01:19:33,890
Whereas when you give the
full chain of reasoning,

1329
01:19:33,890 --> 01:19:37,550
then it becomes clear as to
what led to that response.

1330
01:19:37,550 --> 01:19:42,650
So I think this is the main
mindset behind this technique.

1331
01:19:42,650 --> 01:19:45,610
And basically, this
is something that can

1332
01:19:45,610 --> 01:19:48,170
be used in in-context learning.

1333
01:19:48,170 --> 01:19:53,712
So if you give few-shot
examples, how old was this Teddy

1334
01:19:53,712 --> 01:19:55,170
bear, you give some
number and then

1335
01:19:55,170 --> 01:19:57,690
you slightly change the query.

1336
01:19:57,690 --> 01:20:01,610
And then based on the
reasoning, formatting, and then

1337
01:20:01,610 --> 01:20:05,970
the response, the LLM can adjust
the reasoning and the response

1338
01:20:05,970 --> 01:20:07,130
accordingly.

1339
01:20:07,130 --> 01:20:10,330
And it will force the model
to output some reasoning

1340
01:20:10,330 --> 01:20:14,516
alongside the response,
which shows an improvement

1341
01:20:14,516 --> 01:20:18,490
in basically metrics.

1342
01:20:18,490 --> 01:20:19,350
OK, great.

1343
01:20:19,350 --> 01:20:21,970
And then yeah, something
else that I want to say,

1344
01:20:21,970 --> 01:20:26,290
let's say, you want to do a
task and you want to do it well.

1345
01:20:26,290 --> 01:20:31,490
m you will always have some
samples that do not work.

1346
01:20:31,490 --> 01:20:36,040
And then for them, you want
to have debugging ability.

1347
01:20:36,040 --> 01:20:39,200
And usually when
you debug with LLMs,

1348
01:20:39,200 --> 01:20:41,260
you don't debug
like the old days.

1349
01:20:41,260 --> 01:20:45,080
You don't look at weights at
the intrinsics of the LLM.

1350
01:20:45,080 --> 01:20:48,440
What you want is something
more interpretable

1351
01:20:48,440 --> 01:20:51,040
that comes out of it
in terms of tokens.

1352
01:20:51,040 --> 01:20:53,880
And usually, with
these techniques,

1353
01:20:53,880 --> 01:20:57,480
you can see the reasoning
that the model had before

1354
01:20:57,480 --> 01:20:59,360
outputting a given response.

1355
01:20:59,360 --> 01:21:02,640
And you can debug
basically what went wrong.

1356
01:21:02,640 --> 01:21:07,720
So if you ask how old will
the bear be next year.

1357
01:21:07,720 --> 01:21:12,120
And if in the chain of thought
it says, hey, we're in 2019,

1358
01:21:12,120 --> 01:21:16,160
you know that somehow
in your context,

1359
01:21:16,160 --> 01:21:19,240
oh, maybe I put the
wrong dates in there.

1360
01:21:19,240 --> 01:21:21,000
So you can trace back to--

1361
01:21:21,000 --> 01:21:24,280
you can do some root
causing very easily.

1362
01:21:24,280 --> 01:21:26,140
So it's also used for that.

1363
01:21:26,140 --> 01:21:31,320
And, exactly, in the same
way as other techniques

1364
01:21:31,320 --> 01:21:33,660
that increase the
number of tokens,

1365
01:21:33,660 --> 01:21:36,160
this is a trade off
that you have to manage,

1366
01:21:36,160 --> 01:21:40,040
that it will, of course, take
more time to infer because you

1367
01:21:40,040 --> 01:21:42,720
need to generate more tokens.

1368
01:21:42,720 --> 01:21:45,960
But typically,
we're fine with it.

1369
01:21:45,960 --> 01:21:47,620
Any questions on COT?

1370
01:21:50,960 --> 01:21:52,120
OK, great.

1371
01:21:52,120 --> 01:21:56,880
So now let's take
it one step further.

1372
01:21:56,880 --> 01:22:02,600
So I want to introduce even
to make COT even stronger,

1373
01:22:02,600 --> 01:22:04,760
you can sample your model.

1374
01:22:04,760 --> 01:22:07,880
Several times,
look at the answers

1375
01:22:07,880 --> 01:22:12,560
it generates, and then do
some majority voting to select

1376
01:22:12,560 --> 01:22:15,640
the answer that was
predicted most of the times

1377
01:22:15,640 --> 01:22:16,740
by a given LLM.

1378
01:22:16,740 --> 01:22:20,200
And this is what we
call self-consistency,

1379
01:22:20,200 --> 01:22:24,280
where basically, you sample
responses multiple times

1380
01:22:24,280 --> 01:22:27,960
and then parse
the actual answer.

1381
01:22:27,960 --> 01:22:30,800
So basically, you factor
out the whole reasoning

1382
01:22:30,800 --> 01:22:32,460
and then try to
target the answer.

1383
01:22:32,460 --> 01:22:35,080
And then by majority
voting, you can come up

1384
01:22:35,080 --> 01:22:40,140
to an answer in a
more robust way.

1385
01:22:40,140 --> 01:22:40,640
Yep.

1386
01:22:50,920 --> 01:22:51,460
Yep.

1387
01:22:51,460 --> 01:22:54,360
So the question is, do you
need to have some benchmark

1388
01:22:54,360 --> 01:22:56,020
to know if it's better?

1389
01:22:56,020 --> 01:22:57,220
And yes, absolutely.

1390
01:22:57,220 --> 01:23:01,720
I think the paper operates
on top of all the arithmetic

1391
01:23:01,720 --> 01:23:04,360
and then mathematical
based ones.

1392
01:23:04,360 --> 01:23:06,640
And I think one tangential
question to yours

1393
01:23:06,640 --> 01:23:09,120
is how can you locate
the answer and then do

1394
01:23:09,120 --> 01:23:11,480
measure majority voting on it.

1395
01:23:11,480 --> 01:23:13,960
So typically, you can
put into the context

1396
01:23:13,960 --> 01:23:18,280
some instruction that says,
put the actual answer last.

1397
01:23:18,280 --> 01:23:20,320
So you can just
extract the last.

1398
01:23:20,320 --> 01:23:23,680
People, I think, use regex
based techniques, otherwise,

1399
01:23:23,680 --> 01:23:24,780
to extract the answer.

1400
01:23:24,780 --> 01:23:27,840
Or you could even think
of using some other LLM

1401
01:23:27,840 --> 01:23:29,220
to extract the answer.

1402
01:23:29,220 --> 01:23:32,400
So there is always
a way to do it.

1403
01:23:32,400 --> 01:23:35,720
But yeah, to your point,
yes, we need some benchmark

1404
01:23:35,720 --> 01:23:39,000
and then ground truth
labels to assert

1405
01:23:39,000 --> 01:23:40,230
that this is indeed better.

1406
01:23:53,740 --> 01:23:54,240
Yeah.

1407
01:23:54,240 --> 01:23:56,200
So the request here--
so the question is,

1408
01:23:56,200 --> 01:23:59,180
is it going to be sent to
the same request as example?

1409
01:23:59,180 --> 01:24:01,480
So typically, you
sample it in parallel.

1410
01:24:01,480 --> 01:24:04,280
So basically, you ask your
model exactly what Afshin just

1411
01:24:04,280 --> 01:24:04,940
mentioned.

1412
01:24:04,940 --> 01:24:09,600
You sample from the
probability distribution of BOS

1413
01:24:09,600 --> 01:24:12,680
and whatever tokens you
had, the next token.

1414
01:24:12,680 --> 01:24:17,440
And you do that in several
other kind of branches.

1415
01:24:17,440 --> 01:24:20,160
And you do that, all
of that, in parallel.

1416
01:24:20,160 --> 01:24:25,640
And then you parse the
answer at the end of it.

1417
01:24:25,640 --> 01:24:28,320
So basically, the
latency of this process

1418
01:24:28,320 --> 01:24:32,200
is equal, roughly, to
the maximum latency

1419
01:24:32,200 --> 01:24:35,500
of either parallel generation.

1420
01:24:35,500 --> 01:24:38,000
Because you can do all
of this in parallel.

1421
01:24:38,000 --> 01:24:40,372
So none of these go into
the context of each other.

1422
01:24:40,372 --> 01:24:41,580
They're all done in parallel.

1423
01:24:41,580 --> 01:24:45,240
And then you get
the final answer.

1424
01:24:45,240 --> 01:24:48,160
OK, great.

1425
01:24:48,160 --> 01:24:51,160
All good?

1426
01:24:51,160 --> 01:24:52,360
OK, great.

1427
01:24:52,360 --> 01:24:56,480
So now that we have seen a
few prompting techniques,

1428
01:24:56,480 --> 01:25:01,120
I want to cover together
tricks that people have come up

1429
01:25:01,120 --> 01:25:04,920
with at inference time
to make the generation as

1430
01:25:04,920 --> 01:25:05,880
efficient as possible.

1431
01:25:08,610 --> 01:25:12,120
And basically, yeah, so
in modern day models,

1432
01:25:12,120 --> 01:25:14,420
you have a lot of parameters.

1433
01:25:14,420 --> 01:25:16,640
You want to generate
a lot of tokens.

1434
01:25:16,640 --> 01:25:19,260
How do you do it the most
efficiently possible?

1435
01:25:19,260 --> 01:25:25,600
So I want us to divide this
thought process into two parts.

1436
01:25:25,600 --> 01:25:31,290
So we're going to see what
methods we can come up with that

1437
01:25:31,290 --> 01:25:34,650
give us increased efficiency
on an exact level.

1438
01:25:34,650 --> 01:25:37,350
So you exactly do
the same computations

1439
01:25:37,350 --> 01:25:40,650
as you were supposed to do,
but in a more efficient way.

1440
01:25:40,650 --> 01:25:45,350
And I put some hints as
to what kind of techniques

1441
01:25:45,350 --> 01:25:46,830
we're going to explore.

1442
01:25:46,830 --> 01:25:50,390
So let's try to
look for techniques

1443
01:25:50,390 --> 01:25:52,710
that avoid redundancies.

1444
01:25:52,710 --> 01:25:55,710
Let's try to see what
we could do to manage

1445
01:25:55,710 --> 01:25:57,630
the memory in the best way.

1446
01:25:57,630 --> 01:26:02,230
And also, let's try to
see if we can reformulate

1447
01:26:02,230 --> 01:26:06,750
the equations inside the LLM
in a way that could simplify

1448
01:26:06,750 --> 01:26:09,870
the generation in practice.

1449
01:26:09,870 --> 01:26:12,110
Then there is a second
category that we're

1450
01:26:12,110 --> 01:26:14,030
going to explore as well.

1451
01:26:14,030 --> 01:26:17,270
That is going to focus on
what kind of approximations

1452
01:26:17,270 --> 01:26:21,470
it might be fine to do,
and get a high quality

1453
01:26:21,470 --> 01:26:28,750
answer at a lesser cost,
but to be approximate.

1454
01:26:28,750 --> 01:26:32,870
So we have what kind
of variations we

1455
01:26:32,870 --> 01:26:34,410
could do on the architecture?

1456
01:26:34,410 --> 01:26:37,150
Is there something we
could do on the embeddings

1457
01:26:37,150 --> 01:26:40,030
to make them more efficient?

1458
01:26:40,030 --> 01:26:42,770
And then maybe on the
token prediction side,

1459
01:26:42,770 --> 01:26:48,870
is there something we
could do to make it faster?

1460
01:26:48,870 --> 01:26:50,990
Does that sound good?

1461
01:26:50,990 --> 01:26:53,210
So we have approximately
22 minutes.

1462
01:26:53,210 --> 01:26:57,410
We're going to try to go
through all of them here.

1463
01:26:57,410 --> 01:26:57,910
OK.

1464
01:26:57,910 --> 01:27:02,150
So I grouped the
categories of techniques

1465
01:27:02,150 --> 01:27:05,390
into exact and
approximate techniques.

1466
01:27:05,390 --> 01:27:06,950
But actually,
we're going to look

1467
01:27:06,950 --> 01:27:09,270
at them in a grouped manner.

1468
01:27:09,270 --> 01:27:11,910
First, looking at
the attention layer,

1469
01:27:11,910 --> 01:27:15,430
seeing what kind of techniques
we could have there.

1470
01:27:15,430 --> 01:27:19,390
And then in a second
part, we're going

1471
01:27:19,390 --> 01:27:21,870
to look at the output layer.

1472
01:27:21,870 --> 01:27:26,350
And then see what we can do at
the level of token generation

1473
01:27:26,350 --> 01:27:29,870
to make things as
good as possible.

1474
01:27:29,870 --> 01:27:33,150
So let's start at
the attention level.

1475
01:27:33,150 --> 01:27:38,670
So we have seen that
for every token,

1476
01:27:38,670 --> 01:27:44,310
you need the current token to
attend to the previous ones

1477
01:27:44,310 --> 01:27:47,990
in this masked self-attention.

1478
01:27:47,990 --> 01:27:50,990
So let's say you
generate your sequence.

1479
01:27:50,990 --> 01:27:52,690
You are at a given token.

1480
01:27:52,690 --> 01:27:55,650
So let's say, you have
generated a cute teddy bear.

1481
01:27:55,650 --> 01:27:58,670
And then now you are at ease.

1482
01:27:58,670 --> 01:28:01,750
Now you have the query ease.

1483
01:28:01,750 --> 01:28:05,870
You will compute the key
representation and the value

1484
01:28:05,870 --> 01:28:07,188
representation of ease.

1485
01:28:07,188 --> 01:28:08,730
Because of course,
you have to do it.

1486
01:28:08,730 --> 01:28:10,550
It's your current token.

1487
01:28:10,550 --> 01:28:16,630
But we want to have a way to
reuse the past computations we

1488
01:28:16,630 --> 01:28:20,670
had done to compute
the key representation

1489
01:28:20,670 --> 01:28:23,550
of the previous tokens and
the value representation

1490
01:28:23,550 --> 01:28:26,190
of the previous tokens.

1491
01:28:26,190 --> 01:28:28,830
Does that make sense as a goal?

1492
01:28:28,830 --> 01:28:29,890
Does everyone agree?

1493
01:28:33,550 --> 01:28:35,310
OK.

1494
01:28:35,310 --> 01:28:38,390
And more precisely,
basically, we

1495
01:28:38,390 --> 01:28:44,630
want to find a way for the key
and value matrices to be saved.

1496
01:28:44,630 --> 01:28:48,670
And I'm not
underlining the Q part

1497
01:28:48,670 --> 01:28:51,670
here because of course,
the query corresponding

1498
01:28:51,670 --> 01:28:54,230
to the previous
tokens are not going

1499
01:28:54,230 --> 01:28:57,710
to be of interest for
the present token.

1500
01:28:57,710 --> 01:29:00,670
So it's like the
key and value part.

1501
01:29:00,670 --> 01:29:01,960
OK.

1502
01:29:01,960 --> 01:29:07,310
So there is this concept
of KV cache, where

1503
01:29:07,310 --> 01:29:11,310
the goal is to store
this key and value

1504
01:29:11,310 --> 01:29:18,490
matrices somewhere, and reuse
them directly from the cache.

1505
01:29:18,490 --> 01:29:21,390
So what I just
mentioned here, when

1506
01:29:21,390 --> 01:29:23,750
you want to compute
a given token,

1507
01:29:23,750 --> 01:29:27,510
you would reuse the
key and the value

1508
01:29:27,510 --> 01:29:30,220
directly from the cache
instead of computing it again.

1509
01:29:33,790 --> 01:29:37,390
So this is basically,
representation of what

1510
01:29:37,390 --> 01:29:40,550
we just mentioned here.

1511
01:29:40,550 --> 01:29:41,820
Does that make sense?

1512
01:29:46,210 --> 01:29:46,710
OK.

1513
01:29:46,710 --> 01:29:48,710
Awesome.

1514
01:29:48,710 --> 01:29:51,350
So what else could we do?

1515
01:29:51,350 --> 01:29:51,850
Yeah.

1516
01:29:59,190 --> 01:29:59,690
Yeah.

1517
01:29:59,690 --> 01:30:00,370
Great question.

1518
01:30:00,370 --> 01:30:02,610
So during training,
do we do KV caching?

1519
01:30:02,610 --> 01:30:05,790
I would say during training,
you have this concept

1520
01:30:05,790 --> 01:30:09,390
of teacher forcing, where
you put all your inputs

1521
01:30:09,390 --> 01:30:12,430
and pass it all
together at once.

1522
01:30:12,430 --> 01:30:16,390
So this concept of KV
caching doesn't even come up.

1523
01:30:16,390 --> 01:30:18,030
Yeah.

1524
01:30:18,030 --> 01:30:18,690
But great one.

1525
01:30:18,690 --> 01:30:18,990
Yep.

1526
01:30:18,990 --> 01:30:19,490
Yep.

1527
01:30:37,750 --> 01:30:38,830
Yep.

1528
01:30:38,830 --> 01:30:39,370
Yep.

1529
01:30:39,370 --> 01:30:42,090
Yeah so the question was,
what is the point of all this?

1530
01:30:42,090 --> 01:30:45,990
We want to just reuse
the computations that

1531
01:30:45,990 --> 01:30:46,970
were already done.

1532
01:30:46,970 --> 01:30:48,210
And then your answer is yes.

1533
01:30:48,210 --> 01:30:50,430
Spot on.

1534
01:30:50,430 --> 01:30:51,530
Any other questions?

1535
01:30:54,630 --> 01:30:55,950
OK, great.

1536
01:30:55,950 --> 01:31:01,230
So now that we have seen that
we could cache these quantities.

1537
01:31:01,230 --> 01:31:03,310
So what else could we do?

1538
01:31:03,310 --> 01:31:06,910
So is there something
from last week's lecture

1539
01:31:06,910 --> 01:31:08,990
that we could reuse,
maybe something

1540
01:31:08,990 --> 01:31:14,470
that reduces the amount of
cache, the key and value?

1541
01:31:14,470 --> 01:31:15,800
Do we have some techniques?

1542
01:31:18,820 --> 01:31:19,960
Sparse attention.

1543
01:31:24,620 --> 01:31:26,040
Yeah, that could be.

1544
01:31:26,040 --> 01:31:27,400
That could be, but not here.

1545
01:31:27,400 --> 01:31:30,740
Let's say you're
attending to everyone

1546
01:31:30,740 --> 01:31:33,720
and you focus on the
number of keys and values.

1547
01:31:33,720 --> 01:31:37,460
Is there a way to
reduce this number?

1548
01:31:37,460 --> 01:31:41,300
So just to recap,
we have here, I'm

1549
01:31:41,300 --> 01:31:45,300
operating in the context of
multi-head attention, which

1550
01:31:45,300 --> 01:31:47,700
is you have your h heads.

1551
01:31:47,700 --> 01:31:51,500
So you have h number
of query projections,

1552
01:31:51,500 --> 01:31:54,160
h key projections,
h value projections.

1553
01:31:54,160 --> 01:31:56,780
These are any technique
from last week

1554
01:31:56,780 --> 01:32:00,520
that we could reuse that
could reduce this number.

1555
01:32:00,520 --> 01:32:01,020
Yeah.

1556
01:32:01,020 --> 01:32:01,680
I heard it.

1557
01:32:01,680 --> 01:32:02,180
Yeah.

1558
01:32:02,180 --> 01:32:03,360
Group query attention.

1559
01:32:03,360 --> 01:32:04,820
Yeah, exactly.

1560
01:32:04,820 --> 01:32:11,300
So we had these concept of
grouping keys and values

1561
01:32:11,300 --> 01:32:14,940
together, where basically the
general formulation is called

1562
01:32:14,940 --> 01:32:17,780
group query attention, where
you group these, and then

1563
01:32:17,780 --> 01:32:22,900
the external values h and
1 denotes respectively

1564
01:32:22,900 --> 01:32:27,860
the full multi-head attention,
and then multi query attention.

1565
01:32:27,860 --> 01:32:32,160
And then in modern day
LLMs, a lot of papers,

1566
01:32:32,160 --> 01:32:39,260
they use GQA, with some
group that is sensible value.

1567
01:32:39,260 --> 01:32:43,180
So this is also
something we can do.

1568
01:32:43,180 --> 01:32:44,940
OK, great.

1569
01:32:44,940 --> 01:32:49,500
And now I'm going to go a
little bit into the hardware

1570
01:32:49,500 --> 01:32:51,540
side of things.

1571
01:32:51,540 --> 01:32:56,540
So if we were to store the cache
for all these values in a naive

1572
01:32:56,540 --> 01:32:58,160
way, at inference time.

1573
01:32:58,160 --> 01:33:00,420
So let's say you receive--

1574
01:33:00,420 --> 01:33:04,420
so let's say I'm an
inference server,

1575
01:33:04,420 --> 01:33:07,980
I receive queries
from multiple users.

1576
01:33:07,980 --> 01:33:14,020
And let's say I receive a query
one and I receive a query two,

1577
01:33:14,020 --> 01:33:20,100
a naive way of storing the
key and value matrices would

1578
01:33:20,100 --> 01:33:23,580
be in reserving a
portion of the memory

1579
01:33:23,580 --> 01:33:27,900
at the beginning that correspond
to the entire context length,

1580
01:33:27,900 --> 01:33:30,743
because you don't where
you're going to stop.

1581
01:33:30,743 --> 01:33:32,660
You're decoding because
you stop your decoding

1582
01:33:32,660 --> 01:33:35,780
when you hit the EOS token.

1583
01:33:35,780 --> 01:33:37,940
So you would have
this whole block

1584
01:33:37,940 --> 01:33:42,300
of size context
length, maximum context

1585
01:33:42,300 --> 01:33:44,380
length that could be reserved.

1586
01:33:44,380 --> 01:33:48,660
So one observation is that
it leads to a lot of waste.

1587
01:33:48,660 --> 01:33:52,180
So let's say if your context
length is of size like 2k,

1588
01:33:52,180 --> 01:33:57,660
you have 2k reserved for
a given request 2k there.

1589
01:33:57,660 --> 01:34:01,400
So at any given time, let's say,
you want to get more requests,

1590
01:34:01,400 --> 01:34:03,140
you want to serve more requests.

1591
01:34:03,140 --> 01:34:05,700
Your memory will
very quickly not

1592
01:34:05,700 --> 01:34:13,060
have enough space
to accommodate Does

1593
01:34:13,060 --> 01:34:15,930
these constraints or this
challenge make sense?

1594
01:34:19,180 --> 01:34:21,780
Yeah.

1595
01:34:21,780 --> 01:34:22,280
OK.

1596
01:34:22,280 --> 01:34:26,560
And then there is this paper
that is called PagedAttention.

1597
01:34:26,560 --> 01:34:31,280
And it defines
several quantities.

1598
01:34:31,280 --> 01:34:35,100
So there is this reserved
quantity internal fragmentation

1599
01:34:35,100 --> 01:34:36,800
and external fragmentation.

1600
01:34:36,800 --> 01:34:39,300
Internal fragmentation
is basically

1601
01:34:39,300 --> 01:34:42,740
the space that is being
reserved by the model

1602
01:34:42,740 --> 01:34:44,820
to complete the request.

1603
01:34:44,820 --> 01:34:48,900
And the reserved spot
is the subset of it

1604
01:34:48,900 --> 01:34:52,420
that corresponds to tokens
that were actually being used.

1605
01:34:52,420 --> 01:34:54,180
So it's the kind of
space that's actually

1606
01:34:54,180 --> 01:34:55,480
used internal fragmentation.

1607
01:34:55,480 --> 01:34:57,940
There is nothing in there,
but it was reserved.

1608
01:34:57,940 --> 01:35:02,820
And external fragmentation is
the memory management system

1609
01:35:02,820 --> 01:35:07,760
that doesn't necessarily put
one block one after another,

1610
01:35:07,760 --> 01:35:11,900
but has its own way of
allocating memory blocks.

1611
01:35:11,900 --> 01:35:14,580
So it might leave
some other gaps.

1612
01:35:14,580 --> 01:35:16,980
And they came up
with a system that

1613
01:35:16,980 --> 01:35:22,020
is called a PagedAttention
that is powering

1614
01:35:22,020 --> 01:35:29,220
one inference package
called the vLLM that

1615
01:35:29,220 --> 01:35:34,260
solves this issue by mapping,
like the generation process

1616
01:35:34,260 --> 01:35:36,540
by blocks of fixed size.

1617
01:35:36,540 --> 01:35:42,220
So instead of allocating a
whole portion of the memory

1618
01:35:42,220 --> 01:35:45,580
to answer a given
request, it breaks it down

1619
01:35:45,580 --> 01:35:47,220
by smaller chunks.

1620
01:35:47,220 --> 01:35:52,140
So I think the paper takes
like a value of 16 for blocks.

1621
01:35:52,140 --> 01:35:55,380
So as you can see, let's say
you are in a generation process

1622
01:35:55,380 --> 01:35:57,980
and you have used
a given row, you

1623
01:35:57,980 --> 01:36:04,180
would just start using
another row without wasting

1624
01:36:04,180 --> 01:36:06,300
more space than that.

1625
01:36:06,300 --> 01:36:08,290
And then you have
some dictionary

1626
01:36:08,290 --> 01:36:15,710
that maps token position indices
to basically their cache values.

1627
01:36:15,710 --> 01:36:18,130
So there is a smart
way of managing it.

1628
01:36:18,130 --> 01:36:23,370
And they show that it reduces
fragmentation by quite a lot.

1629
01:36:23,370 --> 01:36:25,810
Yeah.

1630
01:36:25,810 --> 01:36:27,770
OK, great.

1631
01:36:27,770 --> 01:36:31,530
Now let's do something
else with this KV cache.

1632
01:36:31,530 --> 01:36:38,450
So we just saw that you have
your internal representation

1633
01:36:38,450 --> 01:36:43,730
of your token and you project
it into query, key, and value.

1634
01:36:43,730 --> 01:36:47,010
And then key and
value is actually

1635
01:36:47,010 --> 01:36:51,370
something that is of a dimension
that is like non-negligible.

1636
01:36:51,370 --> 01:36:55,450
And you need to store
each copies of it

1637
01:36:55,450 --> 01:36:58,250
in each transformer block.

1638
01:36:58,250 --> 01:37:00,930
So you have many
of these vectors

1639
01:37:00,930 --> 01:37:03,090
that you need to keep track of.

1640
01:37:03,090 --> 01:37:07,250
And is there a way to make that
representation somehow more

1641
01:37:07,250 --> 01:37:09,490
compact?

1642
01:37:09,490 --> 01:37:16,170
And this is a topic
that DeepSeek has tried

1643
01:37:16,170 --> 01:37:19,530
to tackle in a concept called--

1644
01:37:19,530 --> 01:37:24,490
I think it was called
multi-latent attention.

1645
01:37:24,490 --> 01:37:26,370
We're going to see--

1646
01:37:26,370 --> 01:37:28,850
so let's look at
the vanilla case.

1647
01:37:28,850 --> 01:37:31,050
If you are in
multi-head attention,

1648
01:37:31,050 --> 01:37:33,650
then for a given
representation of a token,

1649
01:37:33,650 --> 01:37:40,850
you have h projection matrices
that turn it into a key.

1650
01:37:40,850 --> 01:37:43,490
Does everyone agree with that?

1651
01:37:43,490 --> 01:37:47,650
So the kind of
self-attention formula,

1652
01:37:47,650 --> 01:37:51,570
you have a projection
matrix wk for keys,

1653
01:37:51,570 --> 01:37:56,890
that will project the token
representation into some key.

1654
01:37:56,890 --> 01:37:59,410
And you have h heads.

1655
01:37:59,410 --> 01:38:03,730
You have h such
projections and you

1656
01:38:03,730 --> 01:38:06,490
have h such resulting
embeddings that you

1657
01:38:06,490 --> 01:38:08,610
need to store in your cache.

1658
01:38:08,610 --> 01:38:12,850
Because you have that for
keys, you have that for values.

1659
01:38:12,850 --> 01:38:16,490
That's a lot of
vectors to store.

1660
01:38:16,490 --> 01:38:22,450
And these keys and values,
they are quite long as well.

1661
01:38:22,450 --> 01:38:27,650
So let's see if we
can make it smaller.

1662
01:38:27,650 --> 01:38:31,570
What multi-latent
attention does is

1663
01:38:31,570 --> 01:38:36,730
that it factorizes
these projection matrix

1664
01:38:36,730 --> 01:38:40,090
into an intermediary
space that is

1665
01:38:40,090 --> 01:38:44,730
of lower dimension
than the space of keys.

1666
01:38:44,730 --> 01:38:46,850
You have a first
transformation that

1667
01:38:46,850 --> 01:38:49,490
reduces the dimension
and then another one that

1668
01:38:49,490 --> 01:38:52,050
decompresses it.

1669
01:38:52,050 --> 01:38:56,610
So this is the first
operation that they

1670
01:38:56,610 --> 01:39:01,850
did in order to make the
representation more compact.

1671
01:39:01,850 --> 01:39:05,410
But they did something
else that is very smart.

1672
01:39:05,410 --> 01:39:11,250
They said that the
compression matrix

1673
01:39:11,250 --> 01:39:17,410
could be shared across
keys and values, which

1674
01:39:17,410 --> 01:39:22,010
says for a given token
representation, the cache

1675
01:39:22,010 --> 01:39:28,450
that you need to store for keys
and for values is the same.

1676
01:39:28,450 --> 01:39:31,770
And then you would have
still different matrices

1677
01:39:31,770 --> 01:39:35,170
here for the decompression
part to actually learn

1678
01:39:35,170 --> 01:39:39,010
different representations
for a key and value.

1679
01:39:39,010 --> 01:39:44,930
But one simplification
here has been to share it

1680
01:39:44,930 --> 01:39:47,650
for across keys and values.

1681
01:39:47,650 --> 01:39:52,290
And even better, share
it across the h heads.

1682
01:39:52,290 --> 01:39:58,650
So instead of having h such
embeddings, you have just one.

1683
01:39:58,650 --> 01:40:00,710
And then you do that for key.

1684
01:40:00,710 --> 01:40:01,670
You do that for value.

1685
01:40:01,670 --> 01:40:05,090
So at the end of it, for
every transformer block,

1686
01:40:05,090 --> 01:40:10,210
you have a single
representation per token.

1687
01:40:10,210 --> 01:40:13,210
Does that make sense?

1688
01:40:13,210 --> 01:40:18,690
So not only you have
less things to store.

1689
01:40:18,690 --> 01:40:22,930
The DeepSeek V2 paper also
showed a performance improvement

1690
01:40:22,930 --> 01:40:29,090
that it's kind of credited
some regularization

1691
01:40:29,090 --> 01:40:30,730
consequence of doing so.

1692
01:40:30,730 --> 01:40:34,170
So it learns representations
that are maybe more useful

1693
01:40:34,170 --> 01:40:36,610
and shared across
keys and values.

1694
01:40:36,610 --> 01:40:41,650
So apparently there is also
performance benefits to it that

1695
01:40:41,650 --> 01:40:43,980
is not just hardware based.

1696
01:40:46,650 --> 01:40:47,550
OK, great.

1697
01:40:47,550 --> 01:40:48,850
So now we have seen some--

1698
01:40:48,850 --> 01:40:49,350
Yeah.

1699
01:40:55,870 --> 01:40:56,370
Yeah.

1700
01:40:56,370 --> 01:40:58,990
So the question is, do you
tune the low rank dimension?

1701
01:40:58,990 --> 01:41:01,380
So the dimension itself
is a design choice.

1702
01:41:01,380 --> 01:41:01,880
It's fixed.

1703
01:41:07,210 --> 01:41:10,570
So the question is,
is it the same lower

1704
01:41:10,570 --> 01:41:11,990
dimension for everyone.

1705
01:41:11,990 --> 01:41:14,550
So the dimension size is fixed
and is the same for everyone.

1706
01:41:14,550 --> 01:41:15,050
I think.

1707
01:41:15,050 --> 01:41:16,290
But it's a design choice.

1708
01:41:16,290 --> 01:41:19,490
You could have different ones,
but I think in practice it

1709
01:41:19,490 --> 01:41:20,930
might be the same one.

1710
01:41:20,930 --> 01:41:22,490
Yeah.

1711
01:41:22,490 --> 01:41:25,970
Any other questions?

1712
01:41:25,970 --> 01:41:26,950
OK, great.

1713
01:41:26,950 --> 01:41:28,550
So now we have less
than 10 minutes.

1714
01:41:28,550 --> 01:41:32,290
We are going to cover techniques
that operate at the output

1715
01:41:32,290 --> 01:41:34,450
token level.

1716
01:41:34,450 --> 01:41:39,530
And then start with a concept
called speculative decoding.

1717
01:41:39,530 --> 01:41:44,410
That is a very
interesting method

1718
01:41:44,410 --> 01:41:50,210
that uses some smaller model to
help the generation of a bigger

1719
01:41:50,210 --> 01:41:54,690
model, and then uses
some scheme that

1720
01:41:54,690 --> 01:41:59,280
makes the distribution outputs
match one of the target one.

1721
01:41:59,280 --> 01:42:02,400
So it uses a
combination of tricks

1722
01:42:02,400 --> 01:42:05,760
of using a smaller model to
generate things, and then

1723
01:42:05,760 --> 01:42:10,800
gates it with some
mathematical based properties

1724
01:42:10,800 --> 01:42:13,480
to ensure we get a
distribution that

1725
01:42:13,480 --> 01:42:17,120
looks the one of the big model.

1726
01:42:17,120 --> 01:42:22,160
So here's what is the
lectures, the mindset of it.

1727
01:42:22,160 --> 01:42:24,480
So let's just come back
to our favorite example

1728
01:42:24,480 --> 01:42:26,600
about teddy bears.

1729
01:42:26,600 --> 01:42:30,360
So what you do is
that you ask a smaller

1730
01:42:30,360 --> 01:42:36,340
model, that the paper calls
draft, to generate next words.

1731
01:42:36,340 --> 01:42:38,120
So you have my teddy bear.

1732
01:42:38,120 --> 01:42:39,640
What could be next words?

1733
01:42:39,640 --> 01:42:41,820
So you have one pass.

1734
01:42:41,820 --> 01:42:43,960
You find token is.

1735
01:42:43,960 --> 01:42:46,420
You fit token is here again.

1736
01:42:46,420 --> 01:42:49,120
You find cute and smart.

1737
01:42:49,120 --> 01:42:52,640
Since the LLM is small, this
is typically done faster than

1738
01:42:52,640 --> 01:42:54,760
with the big LLM.

1739
01:42:54,760 --> 01:42:57,080
And then once you
have all of these,

1740
01:42:57,080 --> 01:43:02,760
you put the tokens that are
predicted by the smaller LLM

1741
01:43:02,760 --> 01:43:07,808
all as inputs to
the target's LLM.

1742
01:43:07,808 --> 01:43:09,600
That is like the bigger
model, like the one

1743
01:43:09,600 --> 01:43:12,360
that you use, to
generate probability

1744
01:43:12,360 --> 01:43:16,320
distributions for each of them.

1745
01:43:16,320 --> 01:43:19,760
And then we're going
to see that by having

1746
01:43:19,760 --> 01:43:23,560
some rule on the output
distribution of each

1747
01:43:23,560 --> 01:43:29,440
of these tokens, you can
simulate a probability

1748
01:43:29,440 --> 01:43:34,440
distribution of each token
of each next token that

1749
01:43:34,440 --> 01:43:38,840
looks one of the target models.

1750
01:43:38,840 --> 01:43:44,200
So here's basically how it goes.

1751
01:43:44,200 --> 01:43:49,440
So it looks at the
probability of the token

1752
01:43:49,440 --> 01:43:51,260
that the draft
model has predicted.

1753
01:43:51,260 --> 01:43:54,960
So if the probability
of the draft model

1754
01:43:54,960 --> 01:43:59,880
is bigger than the one of the
draft model in the draft model's

1755
01:43:59,880 --> 01:44:03,480
output distribution, then
you just accept the token.

1756
01:44:03,480 --> 01:44:08,960
Otherwise, you have some
acceptance rejection mechanism

1757
01:44:08,960 --> 01:44:12,920
that either accepts the
token or rejects it.

1758
01:44:12,920 --> 01:44:16,060
And let's say
everything is accepted.

1759
01:44:16,060 --> 01:44:19,420
Then in a single pass,
you are able to advance

1760
01:44:19,420 --> 01:44:22,880
by way more tokens.

1761
01:44:22,880 --> 01:44:25,120
And then if it fails,
then basically you

1762
01:44:25,120 --> 01:44:29,480
resume the process of generation
from that good token onwards

1763
01:44:29,480 --> 01:44:32,860
with some adjustments
on the distribution.

1764
01:44:35,680 --> 01:44:39,940
So one question that you
might ask from all of this,

1765
01:44:39,940 --> 01:44:42,000
this looks like a recipe.

1766
01:44:42,000 --> 01:44:45,120
Why is that matching
the target distribution?

1767
01:44:45,120 --> 01:44:49,760
So if you start from the
law of total probability

1768
01:44:49,760 --> 01:44:54,080
and write each term
with these quantities.

1769
01:44:54,080 --> 01:44:57,500
Then you will find the target
distribution at the end.

1770
01:44:57,500 --> 01:45:00,440
So it's an exercise that
I encourage you to do.

1771
01:45:00,440 --> 01:45:03,680
And the paper that is
attached to the slide

1772
01:45:03,680 --> 01:45:06,660
here demonstrates it
in just a few lines.

1773
01:45:06,660 --> 01:45:09,520
So it's a very simple proof.

1774
01:45:09,520 --> 01:45:13,400
And I think it's a very,
very interesting one.

1775
01:45:13,400 --> 01:45:14,460
Does that make sense?

1776
01:45:14,460 --> 01:45:14,960
Yeah.

1777
01:45:19,008 --> 01:45:20,500
Yeah.

1778
01:45:20,500 --> 01:45:21,000
Yeah.

1779
01:45:21,000 --> 01:45:22,860
The question is, is
that rejection sampling?

1780
01:45:22,860 --> 01:45:25,280
Yeah.

1781
01:45:25,280 --> 01:45:29,415
So some of you might be
familiar with it already.

1782
01:45:29,415 --> 01:45:30,290
Does that make sense?

1783
01:45:33,800 --> 01:45:34,300
Yeah.

1784
01:45:34,300 --> 01:45:37,440
And then one thing that
I didn't say is that

1785
01:45:37,440 --> 01:45:40,520
why did we even put
the last token here?

1786
01:45:40,520 --> 01:45:42,520
We put all the draft
tokens, but also

1787
01:45:42,520 --> 01:45:44,760
the last one that
was predicted because

1788
01:45:44,760 --> 01:45:49,400
by doing a single forward pass
with all these draft tokens,

1789
01:45:49,400 --> 01:45:53,680
you get for free the probability
distribution of the token

1790
01:45:53,680 --> 01:46:01,400
that comes after that you can
then just sample from Qk plus 1.

1791
01:46:01,400 --> 01:46:07,080
So just to give some
summary of the rationale.

1792
01:46:07,080 --> 01:46:12,360
Doing a single pass is
as expensive as doing

1793
01:46:12,360 --> 01:46:15,160
one pass at a time,
because at inference time,

1794
01:46:15,160 --> 01:46:17,300
you're memory bounds back.

1795
01:46:17,300 --> 01:46:21,540
In other words, computations
are not the limiting factor.

1796
01:46:21,540 --> 01:46:23,160
It's basically the
memory that will

1797
01:46:23,160 --> 01:46:24,820
bottleneck your computation.

1798
01:46:24,820 --> 01:46:28,040
So you want to do it
on a smaller model.

1799
01:46:28,040 --> 01:46:29,680
And then on the
big model, you want

1800
01:46:29,680 --> 01:46:32,000
to compute all of these
probability distributions

1801
01:46:32,000 --> 01:46:32,660
at once.

1802
01:46:35,480 --> 01:46:36,460
Does that make sense?

1803
01:46:38,940 --> 01:46:39,440
OK.

1804
01:46:39,440 --> 01:46:41,000
Great.

1805
01:46:41,000 --> 01:46:44,280
And then I want to talk
about one last technique

1806
01:46:44,280 --> 01:46:47,310
that is called
multi-token prediction.

1807
01:46:47,310 --> 01:46:50,550
It's the same-- so by the
way, this previous technique

1808
01:46:50,550 --> 01:46:53,550
was called speculative decoding.

1809
01:46:53,550 --> 01:46:58,390
And then this one is
basically doing the same.

1810
01:46:58,390 --> 01:47:01,950
So it's doing slightly
a different thing.

1811
01:47:01,950 --> 01:47:06,050
But the draft model is
embedded in the same model,

1812
01:47:06,050 --> 01:47:07,410
which is very powerful.

1813
01:47:07,410 --> 01:47:12,630
So basically, it's a model
that attaches multiple heads

1814
01:47:12,630 --> 01:47:16,270
on top of the representation
of the last decoder.

1815
01:47:16,270 --> 01:47:19,150
And the process here is
that at training time,

1816
01:47:19,150 --> 01:47:21,830
it doesn't do next
word prediction.

1817
01:47:21,830 --> 01:47:24,950
It does multi word prediction.

1818
01:47:24,950 --> 01:47:29,870
And at test time, the draft
model is all your heads.

1819
01:47:29,870 --> 01:47:33,850
And your main model is
just the first head.

1820
01:47:33,850 --> 01:47:37,750
So you have all
your draft tokens

1821
01:47:37,750 --> 01:47:41,230
that you then feed
back to the first head

1822
01:47:41,230 --> 01:47:44,170
and then do
acceptance rejection.

1823
01:47:44,170 --> 01:47:46,510
So the paper does
it in a greedy way.

1824
01:47:46,510 --> 01:47:48,250
So it doesn't do it
with this formula.

1825
01:47:48,250 --> 01:47:51,350
Because since the architecture
and then the objective function

1826
01:47:51,350 --> 01:47:55,290
has changed, you don't have this
nice property of finding again,

1827
01:47:55,290 --> 01:47:58,590
the next token
predictions distribution.

1828
01:47:58,590 --> 01:48:01,230
But you have a slight
variation of it.

1829
01:48:01,230 --> 01:48:02,410
And yeah.

1830
01:48:02,410 --> 01:48:04,430
So like the interesting
notes out of the multi

1831
01:48:04,430 --> 01:48:09,030
token prediction is the
change in objective function.

1832
01:48:09,030 --> 01:48:14,470
And then second, the fact that
the draft model and the target

1833
01:48:14,470 --> 01:48:17,990
model are basically
embedded in the same one.

1834
01:48:17,990 --> 01:48:21,270
So don't have to
separate the two.

1835
01:48:21,270 --> 01:48:23,490
And yeah.

1836
01:48:23,490 --> 01:48:25,210
So you do remember this slide?

1837
01:48:25,210 --> 01:48:27,270
We have explored
techniques that can

1838
01:48:27,270 --> 01:48:31,230
remedy each of these aspects.

1839
01:48:31,230 --> 01:48:32,270
So yeah.

1840
01:48:32,270 --> 01:48:35,270
I highly recommend taking a
look at the associated papers

1841
01:48:35,270 --> 01:48:36,430
as well.

1842
01:48:36,430 --> 01:48:40,220
And with that,
thank you very much.